////////////////////////////// very important (and tricky) C interview question ///////////////////////
 #include<stdio.h>
          int main()
          {
            char *p = "Hello World";
            
            printf(p);
            }


////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
🧠 1️⃣ What is happening?
char *p = "Hello World";

👉 p points to string literal "Hello World"

printf(p);

Here is the key point:

👉 printf expects a format string

Prototype:

int printf(const char *format, ...);

So:

printf(p);

means:

printf("Hello World");
🖨 2️⃣ Output
Hello World
⚠️ 3️⃣ Why this is dangerous

This works only because there is no format specifier.

If string contains %, then:

char *p = "Hello %d";
printf(p);   // ❌ dangerous

👉 printf will try to read an integer argument (which is not provided)

This leads to:

undefined behaviour
❌ Example of problem
char *p = "%x %x %x";
printf(p);

👉 May print:

garbage values
memory content
or crash
✅ 4️⃣ Correct way (safe)

Always use format string:

printf("%s", p);
🧠 5️⃣ Why this is important (Interview point)

This is related to:

👉 Format string vulnerability

Used in:

hacking
security exploits
buffer attacks
